text:
to illustrate my point let me tell you some things about me. i had a rough childhood, was on the streets by 15, and i did some questionable shit in those years, no doubt. but what i learned during that time was invaluable to me in this #metoo era:
.
1. let people know that if they fuck with you, there will be severe consequences.
.
2. strike fear into the hearts of those who would harm you. being agreeable is a skill.¬†¬†being crazy is a skill.¬†¬†being unpredictable is the greatest skill of all.¬†¬†learn them all because you will need them for safety.
.
3. the fastest way to evening the playing field between a 200lb man and a 105lb woman is with a weapon. #2a
.
i was raped as a child.¬†¬†young girls are taught to go along to get along. we are taught to look pretty and dance with strangers, even if it‚Äôs uncomfortable.¬†¬†we are taught that it‚Äôs unladylike to scream, and to curse, and to fight. what we aren‚Äôt taught is the power of our own voices and how to create personal boundaries. we don‚Äôt need men to protect us. we need to learn to protect ourselves. this is only half the battle.
.
emasculating young men leads to bottled up aggression. not having friendly touch will do the same. this is why i am a huge fan of contact sports, especially jiu jitsu and wrestling.¬†¬†it is a natural behavior expressed in male adolescents.¬†the bullies, btw, need wrestling and contact sports the most as an outlet. don‚Äôt simply take pity on the kid getting beat up, there‚Äôs some shit going on under the hood of the bully too.
.
if you put touch-starved boys with bottled-up aggression into a world full of girls who were raised to be ‚Äúladylike‚Äù and not fight, scream, curse, and threaten your life if you violate boundaries, do you know what you‚Äôll get? a #metoo movement.
.
this isn‚Äôt getting solved with a fucking gilette advertisement for razors. it‚Äôs like the d.a.r.e program which was ideologically supported but totally counterproductive in reality.  so fathers, raise your daughters well. mothers, raise your sons well. foster self-confidence in your children and raise children who know how to create healthy boundaries and you‚Äôll make a generation that will change the world.

today, being culturally relevant means taking a stand - even if it means alienating people in the process. .

.

text: after years of abuse i could remember thinking to myself,  if i could trade those experiences with anything, what would i be willing to sacrifice not to remember my ‚Äúkid fears‚Äù. and for a long time the answer was my life.  living with the haunting memories, the guilt & the shame were just as bad if not worse than the experience itself.  thankfully, disclosure was the pinprick in the abyss that allowed a glimmer of light towards a path of hope.  we are not alone on this journey of healing. and there are some amazing things we all deserve to experience. #hope #love #istandwithyou #metoo #peace #childhoodsexualabusesurvivor #keepgoing #losangeles #chicago #newyork #rome #paris #dublin #sydney #reportabuse

tessie mcmillan cottom speaking on r kelly. i‚Äôd also say that as we become a more conscious, aware society there is a conundrum we have created. you can‚Äôt condone treating women like shit in one realm and then demonize and say you don‚Äôt want it in another.. it doesn‚Äôt work like that.  similarly, you can‚Äôt practice superiority in one area of life (aka glorified celebrity) and then bitch that you are being oppressed in another realm. 
it‚Äôs not a competition of who is suffering more but it has seemed strange to me that we have come to a place in society where a racist comment will get someones show pulled off air yet we still have artist after artist on the top billboard charts, performing for the grammys etc singing about fucking women, throwing them out like garbage, and flying in new girls.. and we high five this mentality and call it a party or ‚Äúlocker room talk‚Äù

it‚Äôs time to take a closer look at this culture of celebrity and what it really is. we have freewill and can choose to consume whatever we wish, but in doing so we have to be real about the message we are sending to the universe about what we are making ok in our lives.  it‚Äôs hard not to feel like a buzzkill but the truth is you can‚Äôt dap it up with these bros and then go home and honesty say you expect a man to treat your daughter right.  if you want that life accept your choices and the suffering that goes with it.  i could say so much more but i‚Äôll leave it here... .
.
it‚Äôs not that the idea of celebrity is entirely bad or that we shouldn‚Äôt appreciate a star‚Äôs shine, but a cult leader is born via followers who forget their own power. if we choose to be consumers of art created & distributed in a celebrity culture may we simultaneously remember our own creative power and our part in this dance rather than exalt anyone on a pedestal.  if something doesn‚Äôt feel right may you trust yourself and your heart first over what is popular. .
.

text:
there's a concept called bodily autonomy. it's generally considered a human right. bodily autonomy means a person has control over who and what uses their body, for what, and for how long. it's why you can't be forced to donate blood, tissue, or organs. even if you're dead. even if you'd save or improve 20 lives. it's why someone can't touch you, have sex with you, or use your body in any way without your continuous consent.

a fetus is using someone's body parts. therefore under bodily autonomy, it is there by permission, not by right. it needs a person's continuous consent. if they deny or withdraw consent, the pregnant person has a right to remove them from that moment. a fetus is equal in this regard because if i need someone else's body parts to live, they also can legally deny me their use.

by saying a fetus has a right to someone's body parts until it's born, despite the pregnant person's wishes, you're doing two things:
1) granting a fetus more rights to other people's bodies than any born person.
2) awarding a pregnant person less rights to their body than a corpse. #shoutyourabortion #metoo #prochoice #myhappyabortion #prolifeisantiwoman #reproductiverights #myuterusmychoice #bodilyautonomy #bodilyautonomyisahumanright #noappologies #noregrets #noshame #beentheredonethat #abortionisahumanright #alwayshavealwayswill #abortion #myabortion #stayoutofmyuterus #forcedbirth #sexualslavery #handmaiden #handmaidstale #rapeculture #absolutedivorse #sexualfreedom #yestoabortion #yestoabortionrights #healthcare #plannedparenthood #istandwithplannedparenthood #rapeculture

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i wrote this after eurydice dixon was raped and murdered in a local park last year. a week or so later la choll was also murdered at the hands of a man, then a few weeks later nia wilson. in november 7 women in australia were murdered in domestic abuse scenarios in the space of 8 days. this week it was aiia maasarwe.

this poem is dedicated to each of these women and to every woman who's name never made it into print... "sometimes a battle cry¬†
sounds more like a battle weep
because a warrior has been slain
without her even knowing¬†
she was a warrior in the first place. 
what girl knows that?¬†
between the braiding of hair and unpacking of the patriarchy¬†
what girl knows that her very existance
is a battle cry
in a hollow landspace
of untold truths and unwhispered secrets. 
what girl realises
that she is more than emotions and expectations
that the act of her opening her voice
speaking her needs
is the raising of a sword
in a battle we did not sign up for
in a fight we did not want
in a role we have been told to play
for centuries.

what girl wakes
knowing she is a warrior
that every full bodied breath is an act of defiance
an act of reclaiming a body
that was stolen before she was even born 
because it is only in these moments
when we are silenced
by the unimaginable greif
of having yet another limb ripped away
from the body our being
when the dust is settling
on the grave of another fallen woman
who was reminded of her place
in a society which insists we are equal
only in these moments
is it undeniably clear

that we are warriors

and our very existence¬†
is a battle cry
in a hollow landscape
of untold truths and unwhispered secrets
and we can not afford¬†
to be silent any longer

i wrote this after eurydice dixon was raped and murdered in a local park last year. a week or so later la choll was also murdered at the hands of a man, then a few weeks later nia wilson. in november 7 women in australia were murdered in domestic abuse scenarios in the space of 8 days. this week it was aiia maasarwe.

this poem is dedicated to each of these women and to every woman who's name never made it into print... "sometimes a battle cry¬†
sounds more like a battle weep
because a warrior has been slain
without her even knowing¬†
she was a warrior in the first place. 
what girl knows that?¬†
between the braiding of hair and unpacking of the patriarchy¬†
what girl knows that her very existance
is a battle cry
in a hollow landspace
of untold truths and unwhispered secrets. 
what girl realises
that she is more than emotions and expectations
that the act of her opening her voice
speaking her needs
is the raising of a sword
in a battle we did not sign up for
in a fight we did not want
in a role we have been told to play
for centuries.

what girl wakes
knowing she is a warrior
that every full bodied breath is an act of defiance
an act of reclaiming a body
that was stolen before she was even born 
because it is only in these moments
when we are silenced
by the unimaginable greif
of having yet another limb ripped away
from the body our being
when the dust is settling
on the grave of another fallen woman
who was reminded of her place
in a society which insists we are equal
only in these moments
is it undeniably clear

that we are warriors

and our very existence¬†
is a battle cry
in a hollow landscape
of untold truths and unwhispered secrets
and we can not afford¬†
to be silent any longer
even if today¬†
all we can do
is weep." #euridicedixon

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:

text:
it's interesting to think about the last ten years and how much my life has changed. .
- got married. - had a baby. - became a doctor.
- started training to be a general surgeon.
- divorced. - became a single mom.
- experienced domestic violence and rape.
- developed ptsd and suicidal ideation.
- went on a leave from work.
- developed stage 3 breast cancer.
- went through chemo, surgery and radiation.
- found strength and courage in spirituality.
- started to heal childhood trauma.
- in process of leaving a toxic relationship.
- moving to a new home to start a better, brighter future.
- preparing to return to residency as a more compassionate and insightful healthcare provider.
- feeling blessed for all this adversity as it's made me stronger, wiser and full of love.
thanks for listening and for being here with me. namaste 
#tenyearchallenge #growth #breastcancerwarrior #breastcancer #cancer #ptsd #deppression #anxiety #suicide #suicideprevention #strength #youarenotalone #metoo #rapesurvivor #domesticviolence #findyourinnerpeace #vibrationalenergy #heal #andsoshedid

today's best price:  get it on amazon! understanding and addressing linguistic disadvantage must be a central facet of the social justice agenda of our time. this book explores the ways in which linguistic diversity mediates social justice in liberal democracies undergoing rapid change due to high levels of migration and economic globalization. focusing on the linguistic dimensions of economic inequality, cultural domination and imparity of political participation, linguistic diversity and social justice employs a case-study approach to real-world instances of linguistic injustice. linguistic diversity is a universal characteristic of human language but linguistic diversity is rarely neutral; rather it is accompanied by linguistic stratification and linguistic subordination. domains critical to social justice include employment, education, and community participation. the book offers a detailed examination of the connection between linguistic diversity and inequality in these specific contexts within nation states that are organized as liberal democracies. inequalities exist not only between individuals and groups within a state but also between states. therefore, the book also explores the role of linguistic diversity in global injustice with a particular focus on the spread of english as a global language. while much of the analysis in this book focuses on language as a‚Ä¶

text:
we are talking 50%! yes, half!between 600,000 - 800,000  people are trafficked across international borders each year.  50% of those trafficked are children and eighty percent are female.  traffickers are men, women and even other minors. they prey on the vulnerable and those who appear to have a need. traffickers are opportunistic and appear to be a beacon of hope to victims when life seems to be most challenging. for victims, this environment fosters trust, but inevitably leads to a life of slavery and horrors beyond comprehension. if you see something, say something. if you are a victim or suspect that a child may be a victim of human trafficking, please call 911 or call the national human trafficking resource center at 1-888-373-7888 for help. all victims of slavery and human trafficking have rights and are protected by international, federal, and state law. 
the hotline is:‚Ä®(1) anonymous and confidential;‚Ä®(2) available 24 hours a day, seven days a week;‚Ä®(3) able to provide help, referral to services, training, and general information; (4) accessible in 170 languages;‚Ä®(5) operated by a nonprofit, nongovernmental organization; and‚Ä®(6) toll free.

text:
gillette‚Äôs ad with a #metoo edge gets mixed reactions
#
gillette‚Äôs new ad campaign invoking the #metoo movement is the latest test of how big consumer brands can navigate social movements to appeal to millennials without turning off customers who either don‚Äôt agree with their message or don‚Äôt believe it is well-executed.the nearly two-minute ad from procter & gamble co.‚Äôs pg -0.01% gillette tries to tackle sexual harassment, bullying and ‚Äútoxic masculinity.‚Äù ‚Äúis this the best a man can get?‚Äù the ad released online monday asks. the ad, which plays on the tagline gillette has used for three decades, ‚Äúthe best a man can get,‚Äù has been viewed about 18 million times on youtube. reaction has been divided: with 901,000 dislikes on youtube and 468,000 likes as of thursday afternoon. in the first three days of the ad‚Äôs release, there were more than 1.6 million mentions of gillette on twitter , facebook and instagram, as well as blogs, forums and news sites, according to data from brandwatch, a social-media monitoring company. tuesday had the most mentions with more than 893,000, above gillette‚Äôs daily average of about 1,300 mentions for the previous 25 days. gillette's new ad puts a new spin on the brand‚Äôs 30-year slogan ‚Äòthe best a man can‚Ä¶

the exchange between william barr and sen. klobuchar:

klobuchar: the president persuading a person to commit perjury would be obstruction. is that right?

barr: that ‚Äî yes.

klobuchar: okay.

barr: any ‚Äî well, you know, any person who persuades another ‚Äî yeah.

klobuchar: okay. you also said that a president or any person convincing a witness to change testimony would be obstruction. is that right?

barr: yes.

klobuchar: okay. and on page two, you said that a president deliberately impairing the integrity or availability of evidence would be an instruction. is that correct?

barr: yes.

klobuchar: okay. and so what if a president told a witness not to cooperate with an investigation or hinted at a pardon?

barr: you know, i ‚Äî i‚Äôd have to know the specific. i‚Äôd have to know the specific facts.

klobuchar: okay. and you wrote on page one that if a president knowingly destroys or alters evidence, that would be obstruction.

barr: yes.

klobuchar: okay. so what if a president drafted a misleading statement to conceal the purpose of a meeting? would that be obstruction?

barr: again, you know, i‚Äôd have to know the ‚Äî i‚Äôd have to know the specifics.

who says a minority senator is powerless?
to save #america we must hold to account the inept, corrupt and amoral unindicted co-conspirator in the oval office: #illegitimate #failingpresident #donaldtrump.

after two years of a rubber-stamp congress that repeatedly and reliably "looked the other way‚Äù ‚Äî the #democrats will conduct real congressional oversight of #trump‚Ä¶ his life will now [and deservedly so] become a virtual and perpetual deep colonoscopy‚Ä¶ 
the saudis. abuse of power. corruption. ethics. kavanaugh. tax returns. obstruction of justice. #russia! 
you name it‚Ä¶ we can really start getting to the bottom of it‚Ä¶all!

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
flashback friday!  to socializing a wirebrain! i am holding her to pose for a picture (fat lotta good it did she is a blur....) when you are working on getting your new puppy out and about it's best to have them on the floor so they have the choice to approach or watch from a distance. 
if your puppy is unsure about getting closer to someone you can ask then to squat down & toss treats.  but socialization is only successful if the puppy thought it was a pleasant experience experience!!!! being drug against their will or being held while someone touches you that would rather not touch you leaves the puppy feeling violated and erodes their trust in you. (and it leaves them no choice but to escalate their feelings of displeasure with a growl, snap, or bite)

when you trust that someone is looking out for you and always has your best interests at heart you are willing to try things even ones you are unsure about.  when you are with someone who only is looking out for their own agenda and doesn't care about your feelings it doesn't make you geel good, about them or the things they ask you to do.

#metoo #gwp #petsmart #socialization #under16wks #puppiesofig #blurry #earlysocialization #socializationdoneright  #germanwirehairedpointer
#dogtip #dogtrainingtip #bigmoosedogtraining

text:
it has happenned to some of us...
there was a time when all i was aware of was the darkness around me and within me.
i was unaware of the light, the door or the way.
most people would think all was well with me. they saw light in me, because i would try to lift and protect others.
i would not see it...even if i invested in some help...and even if some of that help was legit.

no one could truly help me change my belief system.  i had to do it from within...on my own..and with the help of god... once i realized thatvyesterday is gone and that tomorrow does not yet exist, it changed my life... #iseethelight

text:
set in a united states in which half the population has been silenced, #vox is the harrowing, unforgettable story of what one woman will do to protect herself and her daughter. 
on the day the government decrees that women are no longer allowed more than one hundred words per day, dr. jean mcclellan is in denial. this can't happen here. not in america. not to her. 
soon women are not permitted to hold jobs. girls are not taught to read or write. females no longer have a voice. before, the average person spoke sixteen thousand words each day, but now women have only one hundred to make themselves heard. 
for herself, her daughter, and every woman silenced, jean will reclaim her voice. 
this is just the beginning...not the end. ‚Äú#christinadalcher‚Äôs #debutnovel, set in a recognizable near future and sure to beg comparisons to margaret atwood‚Äôs #dystopian  the handmaid‚Äôs tale, asks: if the number of words you could speak each day was suddenly and severely limited, what would you do to be heard? a novel ripe for the era of metoo,  vox (berkley) presents an exaggerated scenario of women lacking a voice: in the united states, they are subject to a hundred-word limit per day (on average, a human utters about 16,000). considering the threat of a society in which children like the protagonist‚Äôs six-year-old daughter are deprived of language,  vox highlights the urgency of movements like #metoo, but also of the basic importance of language.‚Äù‚Äî vanity fair
‚Äúwith language crystalline and gleaming, and a narrative that really moves, christina dalcher both cautions and captivates. the names that come to mind are #margaretatwood, #georgeorwell, and #aldoushuxley‚Äîhad orwell and huxley had a taste of the information age. vox is a book for the #dystopic present. it woke me up.‚Äù‚Äîmelissa broder, author of the pisces 
publisher: berkley
publication date: august 21, 2018
#acpl #librarylife #bibliophile #fiction #dystopianbooks

text:
men (and frankly, some women too), pay attention. most of you (especially those who follow me) get this and i‚Äôm grateful for it, but some don‚Äôt.
.
.
because a woman embraces her sexuality, and expresses as much via the way she dresses (or doesn‚Äôt dress), dolls herself up, the words she uses, the career she chooses, the photos she takes or otherwise. it does not mean she wants sex or is even thinking about sex. it does not create an invitation for over the top comments, harassment or false assumptions.
.
.
dare to celebrate any woman who simply feels comfortable putting herself out there, and who expresses herself in a way that makes her feel healthy, happy, creative, sexy, alive and empowered.
.
.
allow her to do so in peace without the false assumptions, catcalls or judgments. please! always keep it classy with reactions well thought out. that is all. have a nice day! üòäüôèüèªüñ§
.

warning: sexual assault/harassment/rape

i was 9 years old, it was a lord ganesh‚Äôs festival that day.
my cousin brother , who back then was 18 years old was laying beside me. we were watching the tv laying on the bed then he slid hands up my tshirt, and then down my pants. he molested me. i didnt understand at that age what was happening.
after that whenever we met at family functions, he would come too close, which i found very uncomfortable but did not understand at the of 11-12 how to say no, all i did was push him away.. when i was in 9th grade, i confronted him and asked him why did he do it. at first he denied and said he didnt do anything like this.. then he said sorry like a 50 times. i still havent told my parents about it, but when he sees me today that i am 17 years old.. i can see fear in his eyes because now he knows i have the power. he since i confronted him has not ever bothered me. #metoo #metoomovement #nomore

text:
üå∏ book review üå∏
.
i finished the book of essie yesterday. this book was not exactly what i expected when i picked it up. i was interested in the story the whole way through and definitely never wanted to stop reading, but i didn‚Äôt love it if that makes sense. the premise was so interesting. girl in super religious family (who has a reality tv show a la ‚Äò19 kids and counting‚Äô no less) winds up pregnant and needs out, while the family needs to keep the secret to maintain their super religious image. essie takes matters into her own hands so i do appreciate her as a heroine. she‚Äôs courageous and ingenious. she‚Äôs learned how to use the tv ratings and pandering to the public that her family are enslaved by, to her advantage. but the relationship between her and roarke never felt genuine to me. his character wasn‚Äôt fleshed out enough at all. without giving too much away, he has a secret which is why essie targets him as her escape route. i get that. i just didn‚Äôt buy him. i didn‚Äôt believe. the other main character, liberty, a journalist who is hired to tell essie‚Äôs story is also not believable enough for me. she too has a religious background that she has escaped and a traumatic past. but her character is insubstantial to me.
.
what i liked about the book was the premise - slightly sensational but an interesting commentary on the hypocrisy embedded in some religious circles that tout family values. i guessed essie‚Äôs secret before it was revealed and at that point i certainly wanted her to burn the house down so to speak. she‚Äôs also a timely heroine in a world that‚Äôs finally talking about sexual assault and acknowledging #metoo. so i really really wanted to like this book. i think i just didn‚Äôt love the writing... the characters could have been so weighty and they just weren‚Äôt. and i felt it relied too much on the sensational aspects of the plot to hide the lack of character and story development. there were a lot of missed opportunities in this book and that almost made me angry. bc it could have been so good.
.
overall i am giving the book of essie üå∏üå∏üå∏ violets. and to be honest i feel that‚Äôs a bit generous. anyone else agree? #notjustaprettybook

we explored the topic of sexual violence and how some voices have been left out of the global #metoo narrative in both ghanaüá¨üá≠ and canadaüá®üá¶.
.
over many months maxine and i poured our hearts into this piece, crafting together the stories of survivors and victim advocates in both countries. through a few script overhauls, audio fine-tuning and dozens of conversations over messenger with crazy time differences, we did it and we are so privileged to be able to share these stories.
.

text:
.
.
healing is difficult (but i'm so much stronger now)

head spinning round and round like the 
exorcism to throw you from my head and chest. 
all night i
looked for answers 
in bottle's bottoms, in 
neighborhood's arms; i lit my last cigarette while 
gasping for air under the pressure of your hands.
.
.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company‚Äôs problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you‚Äôre building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person‚Äôs psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the ‚Äútraining set‚Äù refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your ‚Äúfeature set‚Äù: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it‚Äôs facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data ‚Äì the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you‚Äôre trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
‚Äúhope is a discipline‚Äù - mariame kabe.
.
although i often despair, i refuse to give up hope that we can change the systems. part of that is marginalized sexual assault survivors reclaiming the me too movement.
.
let‚Äôs face it - the mainstream me too movement was never meant for marginalized survivors even though a black woman created #metoo. we haven‚Äôt been abandoned or neglected - mainstream white cis hetero abled ‚Äúfeminism‚Äù - never planned to include us. but tarana burke does.
.
#metoo began over a decade ago on myspace when tarana burke had a conversation with a young survivor and wished she had just said ‚Äúme too.‚Äù it is meant to connect survivors to each other and to resources to heal. that is still burke‚Äôs purpose. however, it has been coopted & diluted as it became popularized by white ‚Äúfeminists‚Äù like alyssa milano in october of 2017.
.
milano used it to ‚Äúprove‚Äù to the world how many people, largely women, had been sexually assaulted or harassed. that‚Äôs not what me too was intended to do. in fact, the popularized me too movement looks nothing like burke‚Äôs and what she continues to work on.
.
the popularized me too movement was always meant for: the rose mcgowan‚Äôs of the world. not the lupita nyong‚Äôos, despite the fact both were targeted by the same predator (weinstein). not biwoc, not sex workers, not prisoners, not disabled people, not tgnc people.
.
you saw the ‚Äúrose army‚Äù spring up overnight as nyong‚Äôo was shoved to the side, even as mcgowan spouted erasive racist bullshit against black women specifically. tarana burke was not credited and to this day is often referred to as ‚Äúthe woman who created #metoo‚Äù rather than by her name.
.
so i‚Äôll keep talking about how rape & being punished or blocked from support manifests along intersecting power lines. but we can‚Äôt just talk about the pain.
.
we need to heal. we need true solidarity. we need to lay aside fragility, from any privileges we may have, and we need to support & defend the most vulnerable.
.
let‚Äôs reclaim me too with burke & support its original purpose - radical healing & community.
.

text:
there's a lot of talk these days about ‚Äúboys being boys‚Äù...about toxic masculanity, the #metoo movement and gender. as a mother of boys i am praying hard for my sons. .

from the moment we discovered a boy was forming in my womb we were taught the difference in their anatomy, hormones and growth expectency. .

as fully formed humans, i honestly was unprepared for how rambunctious and energetic these little men are. they can't sit still for long periods and favor learning by doing, rather than sitting and reading. one loves sports, the other loves art, another loves performing -they love all things! .

as they continue to grow i hope they love themselves, stand up to negative energy, respect all people and marry someone who honors their role in the partnership. .

because there is a difference between men and women. .

when they diet alongside their wives, they will lose weight faster. when they have heavy boxes to move, they will have more muscle. when it's time to grow a family, one person will be responsible for carrying those babies. . ...and it won't be my sons. .

growing up with an ambitious mother and disabled father will teach them many things. they will know they don't have to fit in a box. they don't have to be defined by what society tells them they should be (their mama didn't! lol) they can be anything but they can't do everything. respect how you and others were designed - because you are different. what matters most is you live a life of integrity, honor, faith, love and service. .

i believe in our boys. .
#gillettead #toxicmasculinity #ibelieveinourboys #momofboys

from the moment we discovered a boy was forming in my womb we were taught the difference in their anatomy, hormones and growth expectency. .

as fully formed humans, i honestly was unprepared for how rambunctious and energetic these little men are. they can not sit still for long periods and favor learning by doing, rather than sitting and reading. one loves sports, the other loves art, another loves performing -they love all things! .

as they continue to grow i hope they love themselves, stand up to negative energy, respect all people and marry someone who honors their role in the partnership. .

because there is a difference between men and women. .

when they diet alongside their wives, they will lose weight faster. when they have heavy boxes to move, they will have more muscle. when it is time to grow a family, one person will be responsible for carrying those babies. . ...and it will not be my sons. .

growing up with an ambitious mother and disabled father will teach them many things. they will know they do not have to fit in a box. they do not have to be defined by what society tells them they should be (their mama didn't! lol) they can be anything but they can not do everything. respect how you and others were designed - because you are different. what matters most is you live a life of integrity, honor, faith, love and service. .

i believe in our boys. .
#gillettead #toxicmasculinity #ibelieveinourboys #momofboys

text:
as i spoke to one of my cousins today i realized lots of blacks don't know this. these are things that many older people may not but not a lot of young blacks.

after 7 years, you get your bad credit erased off your credit report. you just have to write the companies that  you have debt with until they remove.

i don't think it applies for college or medical but for any non government debts it should.

from an outside the matrix pair of lenses, you can tell the people that run this world know your history book better than you do. most of the rules that they incorporate in corporations stem from the bible. as an example this exact 7 year debt law stems from the bible. they are supposed to release the debts completely not just remove it off your credit report,  but this is satan's land, so that won't happen.

deuteronomy 15 king~

15 at the end of every seven years thou shalt make a release.

2 and this is the manner of the release: every creditor that lendeth ought unto his neighbour shall release it; he shall not exact it of his neighbour, or of his brother; because it is called the lord's release.

3 of a foreigner thou mayest exact it again: but that which is thine with thy brother thine hand shall release;

4 save when there shall be no poor among you; for the lord shall greatly bless thee in the land which the lord thy god giveth thee for an inheritance to possess it:

text:
less than two years ago, my heart was broken more than i honestly ever thought it could be; it was broken so throughly because i felt blamed, shamed and betrayed. since, i‚Äôve learned that we cannot take blame for things which were not in our control, sexual shaming should not be excused, and undeserving secrets should not be held sacred. 
i‚Äôve also learned how incredibly deep misogyny can run.
.
i‚Äôve always considered myself ‚Äústrong‚Äù, invincible in many ways... and this is not untrue. but even the strongest amongst us can be hurt to the core, and it‚Äôs not always physically. the worst has been psychological, and caused by those i love most, or think i know best; from this source the hurt is the deepest.
.
unfortunately i have also been disrespected and assaulted in physical ways, more often than not brushing it off, and moving forward chanting ‚Äúi‚Äôm fine.‚Äù and i am thankful that these instances have not affected me deeper. .

i have felt as though these instances are my fault, that i am the villain. i know i am not perfect; no one is. yet no one should be shamed or exploited for sexuality, sexual openness, sexual preferences; 
no one should be abused, mentally or physically, for any of these reasons (or any reason at all).
.
it is time for me to open up and say it has happened- to me and millions of others, and this is not ok.
abusers cannot be excused or redeemed due to intoxication or misunderstanding. just because abuse isn‚Äôt consistent, does not mean it‚Äôs invalid. .
.
those of us who have been treated this way, should do everything in our power not to brush it off, and help make excuses. sometimes it‚Äôs too painful; sometimes we are too good at justification, and that happens. perhaps negative feelings come out progressively, over a long time, as they did for me, and only then can you process the deep damage an individual or individuals have done to you. .

it terrifies me to broadcast this to the world. but here it is. please examine your actions, your words, your privilege, your intentions. teach your children about consent. listen when people are ready to process. believe the words you are told. 
#metoo #stopslutshaming #slutlife #sexpositive

text:
@womensmarchphilly üîä#weshallbeheardüîä
we are beyond excited to once again host and organize the 3rd annual women's march on philadelphia on january 19th, 2019. our theme this year is "we shall be heard"!
üîäwe shall be heard in our neighborhoods as we organize for action against gun violence, racism, antisemitism and islamophobia.
üîäwe shall be heard in the workplace where we expect equal pay for equal work and say #timesup to sexual harassment and assault.
üîäwe shall be heard by the politicians who represent us on women's reproductive rights including safe and legal abortion, low cost healthcare for all, free college tuition, lgbtq rights and anti-discrimination policies, a pathway to citizenship and immigration reform, protection for the right and the ability for all citizens to vote and climate change policy.
üîäwe hope that you will join us at 10am at eakins oval as we march down the ben franklin parkway to the philadelphia art museum where we will rally with a list of amazing speakers that represent all that we are fighting for.
üîäwith only one day to go, we cannot do this without your help! our organization is an all volunteer board that is dedicated to these causes and donates our time to the planning and execution of this amazing event. donations are needed to pay for all of the various vendors for the event including sound, audio/visual, tents, ada seating, portable restrooms, lighting, etc...to do this right we need $50,000. if everyone who‚Äôs attended the march donates $5 we will meet our goal! thank you for your support!üôèüèæ
.
üîäto donate: https://donorbox.org/women-s-march-on-philadelphia
.
üîäto read more click here: http://www.womensmarchphl.com
.
.

as events to celebrate the women's march commence this weekend, it is important to take the time to recognize the women of colour who have contributed to the widespread conversations around sexual assault and consent awareness.

tarana burke coined the phrase ‚Äúme too‚Äù more than a decade ago as a way to help women who experienced sexual violence. yet, her role in the movement has been overshadowed. the media began crediting alyssa milano, an actress and activist, with founding the movement that burke has worked in since she was 14, and crediting milano with the hashtag that burke began using as early as 2006. the misstep highlighted a common problem: many feminist movements are often whitewashed when they‚Äôre brought into mainstream conversations, overlooking women of color who created them.

speaking live at a concert in 2018, burke reminded every woman of colour that the #metoo movement is theirs, even if the media doesn‚Äôt recognize it. ‚Äúwe have the power to move the needle around sexual violence in our community together. we don‚Äôt need validation from anyone to do that work, we can validate ourselves,‚Äù she said. ‚Äúi‚Äôm here to say to you black women and girls that you deserve safety and you deserve protection, and i‚Äôve committed my life to ensuring that you have it,‚Äù she said.
.
.

text:
ever find yourself supporting someone that makes you scratch your head every time you interact? #ick .
me too. .
this time, it was my old auto shop always - questionable humor, almost locker room type talk every time i was uncomfortably waiting for my car... i gritted my teeth and dealt with it. like, just not quite enough to make a move. then i was talking with a friend who suggested @coopauto - so i scheduled a check up this morning... #autoshop .
i was greeted with friendly smiles, crystals on the front desk, and a locally handmade gnome mosaic as i walked in! #lifebychoicenotchance .
if you‚Äôve seen my posts, you know we are a bit of a gnome tribe...
.
you also may know that i want to support good people doing good business! these folks even called me a lyft to get to my office. dang. that‚Äôs awesome customer service!
.
#home #synchronicity #votewithyourdollars #goodbusiness #smartbiz #gnomesarepeopletoo #metoo #customerservice #consciousness #solid #morninggift #nomorebs

.
.

text:
from 1)denial to 2)awareness to 3)freedom - taking that 3rd simple step.

i get it, we live in an age of sharing. it means that a lot of things that were hidden before, get exposed - including our emotional, mental and physical struggles. in the 20th century we were supposed to put on a brave face and keep going no matter what. admitting and exploring our pain was only for hippies, spiritual seekers, broken people and professional therapists. 
well, the identification has certainly swung from one end of the spectrum to the other, from being a tough survivor to being a vulnerable sharer. if you have not engaged with any #metoo you might miss the boat, you might not belong. 
the 21st century is quickly becoming a dumping ground for exposure, a nursery for stories of pain. 
you might find it weird, that the above text is coming from a professional coach, therapist, seminar leader in emotional, mental and physical wellbeing. and yet, dogma detox requires us to #questionwhatweknow. 
here's the ultimate dogma detox intervention... if you feel that endless sharing of your emotional/mental/physical pain is what you want, please keep going; stay subscribed to that truth and enjoy the status quo. 
however, if you want freedom from it, then it's time for your next step. you have stepped from denial to awareness, now step from awareness to actual freedom. you don't need to stay subscribed to (i.e. ongoingly suffer from) emotional, mental and physical pain. it just requires you to unsubscribe from the rigid truth that tells you 'this is me'. and it's scarily simple once you acknowledge that the pain of identification can be much bigger than any emotional, mental or physical pain has ever been. 
to make it even simpler: you want out of the stuckness?... good, try dogma detox and experience for yourself what happens to the body, mind and being. the experience will outweigh any perceived victimhood, belonging or concept of 'being okay to be vulnerable'. that's all i wanted to expose and share (for now) :-) #dogmadetox #unsubscribe

to read more & to get (free) access to the series, head on over to trustingourmen.com 
we begin jan 30th.

text: as i prepare for the #womensmarch tomorrow, this quote by #gloriasteinem has stuck with me. i distinctly remember the first women‚Äôs march in 2017. i was living in portland at the time and despite the downpouring of rain ‚òîÔ∏è, marching together was a transformative experience. it was the largest international demonstration in #herstory and it ultimately inspired me to root my business in civic engagement and women‚Äôs empowerment ‚úä. in 2018, we took to the streets again, emboldened by the #metoo and #timesup campaigns that brought about powerful change and started critical conversations about sexual harassment and sexual assault. there‚Äôs still so much work to be done. that‚Äôs why this year it‚Äôs as important as ever to keep moving üí•. i encourage all women and men, regardless of your political affiliation, to march in #solidarity tomorrow as we fight for gender justice, racial justice and economic justice. join me. üì£‚ú®

text:
started reading lullaby by @lrwlee and it's awesome. it's like being picked up and getting dropped in a whole new world! in the midst of all the action! it sucks you right in! did i say i liked it? haha if you're looking for something new you should definitely give it a try! you can read the synopsis below!
‚Ä¢
naive... crazy risktaker... or fool in love. who is alissandra?

alissandra, crown prince kovis altairn's sand maiden, flees dream realm to protect him and wake from her father's nefarious schemes. she only prays he can't track her down. but her problems are far from over.

the prince, the most powerful sorcerer in the altairn empire, knows nothing about dream realm, let alone his sand maiden. so when ali is discovered naked in his bedroom, she is accused of malicious motives and being a spy. how will she convince him of her intentions, as well as the danger? 
warning: this book will empower those who say #metoo but contains mature content including sexual abuse. recommended for 18+.

text:
*cw sexual trauma* - you don't need to have a history of trauma to be traumatized by the treatment you receive. when patients are belittled, pressured, coerced, and assaulted by their care providers, that can be traumatic. when patients are in a vulnerable position, feeling ignored and dismissed by their healthcare providers who hold all the power, that can be traumatic. . .

there seem to be more resources becoming available about providing sensitive trauma-informed care to survivors of childhood sexual abuse and sexual assault, and while this is so important and necessary (especially in the #metoo era) we must remember to think about trauma in a much broader way. sexual trauma is not the only trauma that can impact folks' interactions with the health system while accessing reproductive healthcare! adverse childhood experiences are trauma. poverty is trauma. oppression is trauma. racism is trauma. neglect is trauma. intimate partner violence is trauma. historical & intergenerational violence, war, housing instability, incarceration, forced hospitalization, the child welfare system... all of these and so much more can be experienced as trauma! not every person with a history of trauma uses the word "trauma" to describe their experience, but that doesn't make its impact any less valid.
. .

trauma can leave us feeling powerless and unable to cope. when we interact with big systems that do not have our needs in mind and leave us feeling powerless, it can be incredibly traumatizing. this is why trauma-informed care can be framed as a reproductive justice issue!
.
.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
there were days in 2018 that people asked us, "how are you?" and we merely replied, "fine" but deep down we weren't. there were times it felt as though we're all alone in the world, for who could understand the storm in us... still we try to smile, we try for the darkness we face not to quench the little lights we see in others... üòäüòäüòäsometimes we connected with some people and other times they seem like total strangers... even our family members sometimes appear as though strangers...üò∞
.
.
according to world population review, nigeria ranked 68 in countries with the highest number of suicides with	9.5 suicides per 100k. in all the suicides that happened this year, thank you for not being one of them. thank you for facing your demons head on, thank you for facing that storm...üôèüèºüôèüèºüôèüèºüòäüòäüòä you danced in it and came out to the shore. you've been through so much, you've seen so much and though it may seem as though there's nothing to live for, please live for you... we hope and pray for better and happier days in 2019. we love you and god bless you. ‚ù§‚ù§‚ù§
.
.
n.c. desmond
.

debut novel set to release soon. .
.

i see the potential for a world where all youth have engaged fathers, where women have loving, supportive husbands, and where all communities have strong, capable men to lead and protect them. .
.
there are many men who are exactly that, but not enough. not yet. this is why i started the men collective. to unite the men of the world who strive for better, and to serve as an example to those who are in need of it. .
.
to believe in the heroic makes heroes. the future of the world depends on the men we are today, and the influence we have on the men of tomorrow. it may be idealistic to think all men will join us, but i would rather believe in a world full of heroes than a world of men who never become who they were meant to be.
.

text:

text:
ich hab euch gestern was vom gl√ºck erz√§hlt. und passend zu dem thema und dem datum gibt es mal was zwei geschichten von mir. 
heute ist der 18 januar 2019... heute vor 5 jahren bin ich aus afghanistan zur√ºckgekommen. das erste bild ist vom 18 januar 2014 und ich bin gerade auf dem weg nach hause. ich esse gerade ein mettbr√∂tchen. das war f√ºr mich ein so gro√ües gl√ºcksgef√ºhl. der ganze tag war ein unglaublich toller tag voller vielen gl√ºcksmomenten. ich werde diesen tag niemals vergessen. 
auf dem zweiten bild, habe ich meine nato medaille bekommen. ich schaue sie mir heute noch gerne an.. den die bedeutung von der medaille macht mich stolz. stolz, weil ich unglaublich viel mist erlebt habe und durchgestanden habe. in den letzten 5 jahren habe ich sehr viele schlimme jahre gehabt. aber jetzt ist schluss mit dem mist.
es wird nach vorne geschaut zwar mit harter arbeit aber das werde ich schaffen,mit meinen lieben menschen, die mich immer unterst√ºtzen. 
jetzt aber mal was anderes zum thema gl√ºck. 
heute war mein gl√ºcksmoment, als ich bei der meditation gemerkt habe, dass ich tats√§chlich wieder zu mir finde. ich schweife zwar oft mit den gedanken fort, aber es f√ºhlt sich toll an. jetzt freue ich mich aufs wochenende und bin gespannt was alles passiert. bis dennchen ihr lieben ü•∞ #instagram #instagood #instagirl #me #photooftheday #depression #ptbs #borderline #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #lebenmitptbs #life #beasuchtdasglueck #mental #normal #mehrakzeptanz #veterans #postoftheday #isjairre #metoo #meinleben #keepsmiling

text:
do you see this woman? do you really see her? she joined the u.s. army not once but twice. each time she experienced sexual harassment and sexual assault. the second time she joined she was sent to iraq, she wanted to go, she willingly left behind her 18 month old son and 3 year old daughter to serve her country and provide a better life for her children. she knew what she signed up for, she knew the risks, she had hoped that sexual trauma wouldn't be one of the things she experienced over there.

as soon as she stepped foot out of her own state as well as the us, she was dealing with sexual harassment from fellow male service members all of whom outranked her. shortly after arriving at joint base balad (jbb) in iraq she realized she was showing signs of depression and anxiety. however she knew she couldn't talk to anyone, the base was too rife with assaults and all soldiers knew the stories about weapons being taken away or made inoperable for those of us dealing with stress. also jbb was nicknamed mortaritaville for all the mortars that hit the base daily. to the extent that her base was bombed 2-3 times more during the iraq war than all of vietnam, laos, and cambodia during the vietnam war.

she dealt with at least six perpetrators of sexual assault/harassment during her deployment. did she report it, you wonder, no, no because the victims 98%(that's what it feels like) get punished and the perpetrator(s) don't. and still she continued to do her job. she came home, she looked for work, she took care of her kids. she went to the local va hospital within six months of coming off the deployment. she shared everything, every time they asked if she experienced military sexual trauma (mst) she said yes. at least two va claims and eleven years later she still gets denied for post traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), service connection for major depression and anxiety. do you still see her? the veterans benefits administration doesn't, she's invisible, her trauma counts for nothing, not injured enough.
#thatwomanisme #mst #vbadeniesmstclaim #combatveterans #army #invisiblewounds #metoo

text:
i want women and girls to remember that we need to support one another, no matter how strong or vulnerable we are. recognition of women's rights is something that is being nurtured, and is growing every day. in light of #metoo, we have potentially come in bounds in our confidence to speak up against men who have not done the right thing, but many women and girls are still suffering greatly at the hands of other females.
it may be something as simple as exclusion by peers, or as horrific as domestic violence, but it's rife.

we need to make an extra effort for our vulnerable ones. big and little. we need to be conscious of our own actions. we need to be aware. we need to build up those in need, and applaud those who are role models.

don't let our girls give up their goals and dreams.
don't be the woman who didn't act to help.
.
.

name: Jacqui
tweet_full:
i want women and girls to remember that we need to support one another, no matter how strong or vulnerable we are. recognition of women's rights is something that is being nurtured, and is growing every day. in light of #metoo, we have potentially come in bounds in our confidence to speak up against men who have not done the right thing, but many women and girls are still suffering greatly at the hands of other females.
it may be something as simple as exclusion by peers, or as horrific as domestic violence, but it is rife.

we need to make an extra effort for our vulnerable ones. big and little. we need to be conscious of our own actions. we need to be aware. we need to build up those in need, and applaud those who are role models.

do not let our girls give up their goals and dreams.
do not be the woman who didn't act to help.
.
.

text:
from my friend elliott battzedek.  brilliant and so well written.  i wish i could articulate and write this well.

did you read the nyt obit for mary oliver? it is so condescending. a few choice bits:

1. "more than 20 volumes of verse to her credit" - poets who have won pulitzer prizes  and national book awards write poetry, not "verse" - that was an intentionally belittling word choice, as "verse" carries connotations of "light verse" and "spinster aunts who write couplets about the family history." 2."seemed to endear her work to a broad public, including clerics, who quoted it in their sermons" - again, intentionally condescending word choices. who says "clerics?" how did that pass any editorial process?  why not ministers? or liturgists? same for "sermons" - as a liturgist myself, i use her poems in my liturgy, as do so many others, because the language is accessible while the emotions are deep and never saccharine. putting "clerics" and "sermons" together is just a way of conveying the writer felt her poems were "preachy" - which is a cheap jibe.

3. "celebrities like laura bush and maria shriver" - millions of people loved her work. why list these two particular names? do you want us to believe that the nyt cites laura bush here as anything other than a burn?

4. "ms. oliver spoke of having been sexually abused as a child, though she did not elaborate." - have you learned nothing from coverage of #metoo about believing women? this  wording is intentionally suspicious, implying that because she did not elaborate she might not be believable.

5. " given its seeming contradiction ‚Äî shallow and profound, uplifting and elegiac ‚Äî ms. oliver‚Äôs verse is perhaps best read as poetic portmanteau" - again, the word "verse" and a resistance to even calling her work "poetry" but only "poetic portmanteau." some parts of the obit are much more fair, even generous. obits are not just to lavish praise, but neither are they the chance for a critic to get in one final hit. this piece must have been written by more than one person, as it switches voices paragraph to paragraph. more than one writer, but no editor.

text:
news flash: hook grip fucking sucks. but the cool kids do it sooooo #metoo. 
in reality, i like to use it as an alternate grip for sub maximal training. using the same under over grip all the time develops bad habits like uneven torquing and elbow tendonitis, not bueno.

me, last offseason: "i get good carryover from volume with deads boss can we bump that up this cycle?"
@joesullivanpowerlifter: "hold my energy drink"
*gives me 8-10 sets* 
if your programming doesn't excite and scare you a bit, you ain't training hard enough.

extra bonus fun fact:
powerlifting gives you a bad habit of tensing up while sparring, so in the later rounds you get touched up because your shoulders are dead. rip modeling career.

#elitefts #morphogennutrition #thepebble #strongthesullyway #howmuchyabench #notthatmuch #usmc #powerlifting #uspa #bethefuckingbestever #projectrock #deadlift #bamabricksquad

text: toxic masculinity ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî when most people talk about toxic masculinity, they do not mean masculinity is toxic. what we mean is specific things associated with masculinity is toxic, such as: bullying, violence, showing no emotion, not crying, having to like sports, having to do traditional male jobs, disrespecting others, catcalling. we do not want people to stop being masculine, we want to stop these things associated with masculinity, and stop using gender as an excuse. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî #mensrights #mensrightsactivist #mensrightsmovement #feminism #meninism #feminist #gillete #boycottgillette #toxicmasculinity #masculinity #catcalling #metoo #commercial #empowerment #men #women #boys #girls

text_retweet:
ah...the satisfaction of removing the last bit of tape guide for a grid installation.
the wash (as it seams) opens january 21 @msuunionartgallery #repost
.
i am at michigan state university to engage the community and to offer nassar survivors, all survivors, an opportunity to participate in the panty project. 
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

she spoke to honorees @lauradern and nina shaw from @timesupnow, monica ramirez of @campesinasunite and @enyamayaro from @unwomen's @heforshe campaign; she also chatted with luminaries like @doloreshuerta and the chair of fmf's nobel nomimated campaign for afghan women and girls, mavis leno, and featured guests like @camrynmanheim and @milckmusic of the #icantkeepquiet movement.

to illustrate my point let me tell you some things about me. i had a rough childhood, was on the streets by 15, & i did some questionable shit in those years, no doubt. but what i learned during that time was invaluable to me in this #metoo era:
.
1. let people know that if they fuck with you, there will be severe consequences.
.
2. strike fear into the hearts of those who would harm you. being agreeable is a skill.¬†¬†being crazy is a skill.¬†¬†being unpredictable is the greatest skill of all.¬†¬†learn them all because you will need them for safety.
.
3. the fastest way to evening the playing field between a 200lb man & a 105lb woman is with a weapon. #2a
.
i was raped as a child.¬†¬†young girls are taught to go along to get along. we are taught to look pretty & dance with strangers, even if it‚Äôs uncomfortable.¬†¬†we are taught that it‚Äôs unladylike to scream, & to curse, & to fight. what we aren‚Äôt taught is the power of our own voices & how to create personal boundaries. we don‚Äôt need men to protect us. we need to learn to protect ourselves. this is only half the battle.
.
emasculating young men leads to bottled up aggression. not having friendly touch will do the same. this is why i am a huge fan of contact sports, especially jiu jitsu & wrestling.¬†¬†it is a natural behavior expressed in male adolescents.¬†the bullies, btw, need wrestling & contact sports the most as an outlet. don‚Äôt simply take pity on the kid getting beat up, there‚Äôs some shit going on under the hood of the bully too.
.
if you put touch-starved boys with bottled-up aggression into a world full of girls who were raised to be ‚Äúladylike‚Äù & not fight, scream, curse, & threaten your life if you violate boundaries, do you know what you‚Äôll get? a #metoo movement.
.
this isn‚Äôt getting solved with a fucking gilette advertisement for razors. it‚Äôs like the d.a.r.e program which was ideologically supported but totally counterproductive in reality.  so fathers, raise your daughters well. mothers, raise your sons well. foster self-confidence in your children & raise children who know how to create healthy boundaries & you‚Äôll make a generation that will change the world.

text:
i dont support the #metoo movment .
this stupid #label seems to be giving everyone validation to stay within a victim mentality. i don't see their being any reason to spiral into this movement.

what needs to be addressed, is that unfortunate events have happened, if i was 5 years of age or 13, 18 or 27, if your following this movement your conciously choosing to stay in victim mentality, you #painbody

the wiser thing to do is to, accept that what happen is the past but dont allow it to keep you in your past. that isnt the way to move into your pleasure body, victim mentality will only lower your viberation

picture this, so you have a folder of empty bad or emotionless experiences. personally this folder maybe the reason you stay in the past and lack to stay present.

what we want to be doing, is creating a new folder, to create new experiences as new experinces will create new emotions, and as we know emotions are our drivers which will create new habbits and a healthier mindset.

comment
a.) i agree, lets move past pain and choose pleasure
b.) i disagree, we need to make a stand
