text_retweet:
#repost @nathanhasasong with @get_repost
„Éª„Éª„Éª
men are vulnerable. we‚Äôre taught that we‚Äôre not supposed to be, but we are. we‚Äôre vulnerable to heartache, mental illness, trauma, and so on. but male vulnerability is often equated with weakness, which in turn is associated with shame. so why would a man decidedly make himself vulnerable to get the help he needs? how does a man know when vulnerability is no longer a weakness but a strength? who makes that determination? that very shame associated with being vulnerable is exactly why suicide is the leading cause of death in men under 50. working with teen boys, i battle this stigma daily, trying to redefine what it means to be vulnerable to young men who‚Äôve already been brainwashed to believe that silence and violence are the only two acceptable responses to hardships in life. i see their pain, their desire to break through and reach out, and the shame that holds them back. men suffer too. our mental health matters. it‚Äôs time we break through the barriers of shame, for ourselves and for the next generation who watches us so closely.

text:
most people don‚Äôt realize that the equal rights amendment (era) that was passed in congress in 1972 still hasn‚Äôt passed the ratification process, in which at least 38 out of the 50 states have to re-affirm. as of june of this year we only have one more state to go to make that 38 goal that started over 35 years ago. additionally, most people don‚Äôt realize that women have not had the right to vote for even a 100 years yet. the 19th amendment passed by congress in 1919 and it was ratified in 1920. 
so, you ask me why i will march tomorrow in seattle. it‚Äôs because i march for my rights, my fellow sisters all across the world, the women who came before me, and the women who will come after. we cannot become complacent in our attitudes towards equal rights regardless of gender, ethnicity, creed, or orientation. 
i hope to see you there.

text:
have any of you ever struggled with acne?
.
me too! i have had acne for 10 years! the first several years i had cystic acne on my back and my face. it was a challenge for self love - to learn how to take care of myself with the love and respect i deserve.
.
in the beginning, i went to see doctors for my skin and hormonal imbalances and every time they‚Äôd send me home with a prescription and would tell me diet and lifestyle had nothing to do with my health issues. now, i i used to get pissed off at them but then i learned that they weren‚Äôt trained in diet and nutrition, so they didn‚Äôt know this truth themselves. i took it into my own hands to heal my body, to pursue healthier lifestyle choices, diet, and hygienic practices.
.
changing my external lifestyle helped tremendously but it wasn‚Äôt until i learned to love my acne and what it taught be - that it started to fade away. going vegan and gluten free and quitting the use of any facial products were the steps i needed to take for self love and self care.
.
to hear more about my acne journey and how i overcame it, find the link in my bio to my youtube channel @adventuresacross. i‚Äôm so grateful for my acne journey, (and this guy @sandersonwellness for joining me, even though he didn‚Äôt have to üòò) and how it taught me how to love myself ü•∞.
.
what is your favorite self care activity?
.

text:
before making #metoo allegation, file official complaint with complaints committee: dia mirza

actress dia mirza says women have long endured a culture of silence, and because of that, sexual predators have got encouragement.
filmmaker rajkumar hirani is the latest name to be called out for sexual harassment with a woman "assistant" alleging in an article in huffpost india that he sexually abused her more than once between march and september 2018 while working on "sanju". reacting to this, dia said: "he has been a very close friend of mine and i have worked with him since so many years, so to comment on his case will be unfair on my part because i don't know the details. i just want to say that before making an allegation, it's very important to file a complaint with the icc (internal complaints committee) and they should carry out a due investigation on entire matter because without that, it's impossible to really understand the full extent of what has happened and it can be deeply damaging to everyone." for more news and updates, subscribe to www.english.mathrubhumi.com

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i literally had shivers reading about the tragic death of aiia maasarwe ‚Äî yet another beautiful woman who had so much to offer this world gone far too soon, at the hands of a man with cruel intentions. 
when will this end? 
we all have a right to feel safe. 
yet again this echoes the fear us women so understandably have, all the time. it never goes away. it doesn't get any better.
the fear of walking anywhere at night. the fear of walking with headphones in just in case we can't hear someone coming from behind us. the fear of walking to our cars at night. the fear of getting off public transport as soon as the sun goes down. the fear of walking anywhere with poor lighting and absolutely fearing for our lives the moment we see a figure walking towards us or hearing footsteps behind us. the fear that exists in getting in an uber or taxi with a male driver, which you think we should feel safe enough in. the fear of having to walk past a group of men hurling comments at you as if it's to be a compliment. it never ends...
this is why us women endlessly message each other after nights out to ask each other if we got home okay. this is why my mum messages or calls me if i've forgotten to tell her i'm going somewhere after work to ask me where i am. this is why i only ever have one earphone instead of both in when going for a walk (yes, even when in broad daylight). this is why, when i used to catch public transport home from a night shift, i had my best friend's number ready to call the moment i got off the train as i ran to my car in the dimly lit and empty station car park. this is why i dial 000, just in case, when i have to walk a fair distance back to my car at night, whether it be after a catch up with a girlfriend or a night out. 
this is not a matter of shaming or hating on men, this is about us women having the right to feel safe no matter where we are, what time it is, what we are wearing or what state we're in.
i feel for us women and the fears we all share... it shouldn't be like this. for now, i guess all we can do is look out for each other? üíóüë≠
